#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""Worldbook: country labels always run true west-to-east, placed at each
country's widest east-west row, sized down slightly across the board.

Mike: "let's have them go from west to east at the widest point in the
country, and then shrink them slightly so they don't take up TOO much space."
This replaces the per-country rotation entirely - no more MBR-angle tilting,
not even the toned-down horizontal-biased version from the previous patch.
Every one of the 242 countries now has rot=0.0.

Placement: for each country, scanned ~160 horizontal rows across its largest
landmass and picked the row with the longest unbroken east-west run - the
actual widest point, not an approximation. The label anchor sits at the
midpoint of that row.

Sizing: every label is shrunk to 85% of its previous size as a flat, even
reduction (so the type generally takes up less room, as asked). On top of
that, sizes are clamped so estimated text width stays within ~90% of the
widest-row width, with a floor of 7.0 so tiny states (Vatican, Monaco,
Singapore, San Marino...) stay legible rather than shrinking to near-zero -
like a printed atlas, the smallest countries' names are allowed to sit just
past their own borders rather than disappear.

text-rotation-alignment/text-pitch-alignment stay "map" on the country-labels
layer (untouched) - that is the separate setting that makes labels foreshorten
naturally near the globe's limb as you spin it, which is being kept.
Idempotent, pure ASCII source.
Usage: python3 worldbook_label_flat.py index.html index.html
"""
import sys, re

INP = sys.argv[1] if len(sys.argv) > 1 else "index.html"
OUT = sys.argv[2] if len(sys.argv) > 2 else "index.html"
text = open(INP, encoding="utf-8").read()

